Comment: Nice concise statement! Solvable within 5 minutes and can be used for shortest mode!
I really like this one in fastest and shortest mode

I think you could reword the whole thing.

Give the audience a specific number as a goal and then let them have at it and find a, no "the", combination of letters maybe even spaces and digits (numbers) that get close?  Make it difficult!

And, I'm sorry the letters LD never get into any of the clashes.  So, I want to approve this one but I can't.  If you would kindly replace those then I would approve it for sure.  How about US or your country's abbreviation, sorry any countries abbreviation?

I like this problem. Here are my suggestions:
- Replace N with D in testcases.
- "how many possibilities there is on a license plate" -> "how many unique licence plates can be made"
-"Each country has its sequence" -> "Each country has its own way of building a licence plate"

Goal section
* Please change "it" to "its".
* Please change "numbers"/"Number" to "digits"/"Digit" because "number" includes many possibilities, e.g. fractions and irrational numbers.
* Please specify "(i.e. {{A}} to {{Z}}, uppercase only)" after "Letter".
* Please specify "(i.e. {{0}} to {{9}})" after "Digit".
* Please format L and N as {{constants}}.

Input section
* Please change "numbers" to "digits".

Thanks.
thanks for the suggestion! forgot about the "D"s on test cases lol
